<font color="#FF0000">PROPOSED THREAD(S)</font><br>
<tt>Wed Jul 30 14:00:34 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Art <br>
Thanks for the compliment; I would have liked to have met him.<br>
I have been recently working on the part of the book where I mention intense fear. The type of fear of failing to act and the other fear, real fear, the type where death stand at the door and mocks you with its shadow. And just when you think you faced it all, you find another type of fear where even death stands still, where even death fears to move. Fear where the gates of hell, death and destruction merge into happiness and eternity.<br><br>
I first introduced fear of the unknown in the beginning chapter. when I mention a recollection of the days spent in boot camp and our boot camp instructor.<br><br>
&quot;We knew that he wasn't telling us everything he knew about the war in Vietnam.  He had told us that he had cheated death in the jungles of Southeast Asia a number of times. His number had been up, but somehow he had made it back. Sheer luck had crowned him with the honor of belonging to the choir that sang of the perils of war. <br><br>
He was, however, quite transparent and it was easy for us to see when he spoke from personal knowledge about the war, he displayed a particular form of fear that both scared us and made us hunger for more. It was a fear that announced, many of us would not come back. It was also that type of fear that can only be understood by those that have been to war that have engaged the enemy in combat, those who have had to fight for life and who feared&quot;<br><br>
Mustang Two Four<br>
Great Idea, we can call it Rules of Engagement!<br>
But I want to be able to really open up this time. I'm tired of fan-firing blanks at the practice range. This time I want to lay out some booby-traps, fire a full belt of ammo, all tracers and even pitch in a couple of grenades. As the Sgt. used to say, &quot;We need to fire for effect.&quot;<br><br>
All right, just kidding &lt;G&gt;, I'll take the tracers out, I'll even lay the 60 by my side, but just to play it safe I'm chambering a round into the .45.<br><br>
Seriously, It would be advantageous to us to follow Ed as pointmen in this venture. I believe there are some issues that deserve serious consideration and truthful answers. I have no problem with responding in a serious dialog; I do have a concern that the public and others may not understand the intensity of our concerns and commitments. <br><br>
Perhaps we can test the waters with a topic of genuine interest and concern and see what happens. Sort of do a test run. I do believe that we might need to keep some illumination flares by our side, sort of to keep us all on the trail we're following. <br><br>
Why, I'll even come up with a new handle. We all used nicknames in Nam, never knew many of the guys real names, just their nick names. <br>
But, some didn't mean what they said, like &quot;lucky,&quot; he sure wasn't lucky, Rain Dancer wasn't even Indian and BaBAA, well, he got his name when he fired a 3.5 rocket at the gooks while he was still in a hole, blew out his ear dums but that was the first thing he said afterwards, BABAA!<br>

<p><code>-- Think I'll use SparrowHawk, from now on.  (Cook B. Do I need a handle?) </code><p>


